[There were actually 3 different news reports (21, 26 and 28 Feb,
2003) published by the Post-Courier newspaper related to this disease
outbreak. Rather than provide 3 reports, I have used the 26 Feb
report as the main source and incorporated some information from the
other reports to provide a single piece.
According to Martin Gunther, National Research Institute Highlands
High Altitude Research Center, the disease first broke out at
Sirunki, Enga Province and has spread to all parts of the province
including Laiagam, Kanadep, and Wapenamanda, and at Kwip, Banz, and
Tomba in adjoining Western Highlands Province. The fungus can survive
as mycelium in living potatoes, cull piles, or as volunteers that
overwinter. Plant pathologists in PNG are faced with finding
cultivars that are resistant to the prevailing races of the pathogen,
and that will depend upon selection of available sources of
resistance.
Potato late blight is a major pathogen of potato and is considered as
one of the most devastating diseases in human history. Its main hosts
are potato and tomato in the _Solanaceae_. Disease management depends
on use of several strategies (disease-free tubers for planting,
application of selected fungicides, destruction of potato vines by
chemicals or herbicides prior to harvesting to reduce tuber
infection, and breeding for resistance). The last strategy employs
use of cultivars that have polygenic or field resistance to the
pathogen. In such cultivars, combinations of several minor genes act
together to slow the rate of fungal development and enable the plants
to tolerate infection.
Reference:
<http://helios.bto.ed.ac.uk/bto/microbes/blight.htm> - Mod.DH]
